      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Judging from the following electrostatic potential maps, which kind of carbonyl compound has the more electrophilic carbonyl carbon atom, a ketone or an acid chloride? Which has the more nucleophilic carbonyl oxygen atom? Explain.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcjBYIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--d324ffe285f127f2b8a4679129ec22a3c778c859/OChem_18_PCC_017.jpg\" alt=\"The ball-and-stick model in electrostatic potential maps of acetone (ketone) and acetyl chloride (acid chloride). An arrow points toward the carbon atom that is bonded with oxygen.\">",
